<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br><br>
Put a footnote number in your text to show when you are using another person&#8217;s ideas or words.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip;has been recently identified.<sup>1</sup>
</blockquote>
<br>
This number directs your reader to a footnote at the bottom of your page. The footnote contains information about the work you are citing, including the author&#8217;s name, details of the work, and relevant page number(s).
<br><br>
<strong>FOOTNOTES</strong>
<br><br>
Footnotes are placed in numerical order at the bottom of the page. In the case of most assignment papers and essays where footnotes and a bibliography are used, the footnote can be quite brief (Example B) because the full details are found in the bibliography. However, if you are instructed by your tutor or lecturer to provide a full reference in the footnote the first time a work is cited, see Example A. If the work is cited again, use the short form (Example B). In the short form, the title may also be shortened if it is more than four words.
<br><br>
When shortened references to the same work follow each other with no other references in&#45;between, replace the authorâ€™s name, and title with <strong>ibid</strong> (Example C) and the page number if it differs from the previous citation (Example D).
<br><br>
<strong>Example A</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="footnotes ref-indent-1-27cm">
	<span class="smaller">1. Amelia Smith, &#34;The Influence of Bible Studies on New Zealand Primary School Children, 1945&#45;1982&#34; (master&#8217;s thesis, University of Auckland, 2056), 85.</span>
</blockquote>
<br>
<strong>Example B</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="footnotes ref-indent-1-27cm">
	<span class="smaller">7. Smith, &#34;Influence of Bible Studies,&#34; 23.</span>
</blockquote>
<br>
